WHEREAS, According to the Cleveland Clinic, postpartum 18
psychosis affects between one and two per 1000 mothers, often 19
develops rapidly, and may place the life of the mother and 20
infant in danger related to its symptoms, which may include 21
delusions, hallucinations, severe mood symptoms, and cognitive 22
symptoms; and 23
WHEREAS, According to the Ohio Department of Health's 24
Pregnancy-Associated Mortality Review Program, mental health 25
conditions are currently the leading cause of pregnancy-related 26
deaths in Ohio; and 27
WHEREAS, Mental health conditions affect mothers and 28
mothers-to-be of all races, ages, and socioeconomic levels; and 29
WHEREAS, Pregnant and parenting women with untreated mental 30
health issues experience higher rates of infant and maternal 31
mortality, family fragmentation, lack of prenatal care, low 32
social support, financial and housing instability, co-occurring 33
health complications, unmanageable job strain, difficulty 34
meeting maternal role expectations, and childhood or perinatal 35
trauma, including domestic and sexual abuse; and 36
WHEREAS, The societal impact of perinatal mental health 37
conditions is pervasive, with far-reaching consequences on early 38
childhood development, pediatric mental health, and general 39
family well-being; and 40
WHEREAS, Undiagnosed and untreated perinatal mental health 41
conditions are a silent health crisis in the United States, 42
deserving recognition and action to save lives and improve the 43
health and well-being of America's mothers, babies, fathers, 44
families, and the community; now therefore be it 45
RESOLVED, That we, the members of the 136th General 46
Assembly of the State of Ohio, recognize the importance of 47
perinatal mental health and are supportive of a coordinated 48

